1. RNA Binding Protein Signal Visualization

Three alternative visualizations of the same artificial data has been created. All three visualizations show the same fictitious genomic annotations together with fictitious RNA binding protein data.

Two different datasets are used for this task:

  • anno.csv
  • sig.csv

Each visualization integrates transcript structures and protein signal data, using different plotting techniques:

  • Version 1: Displayed signals in separate tracks for clarity.
  • Version 2: Combined signals in stacked layers.
  • Version 3: Overlaid signals for a compact view.

All visualizations were created using pandas, numpy, matplotlib, and seaborn, and include comments explaining each step of the code.

1.4 : Discussion

The exact properties of our data and the insights we wish to communicate will influence the visualization strategy we use. Each version has pros and cons, therefore we may think about combining components from other versions to produce the best possible depictionof our data.

Version 1

Pros

  1. Separates the data into five subplots(easy to compare different aspects of the data)
  2. Allows customization of each subplot individually
  3. Providing clear annotations.

Cons

  1. Plots may appear crowded(hard to interpret the overall patterns)
  2. Annotations seems chalenging to visualize accurately.

Version 2

Pros

  1. Heatmap provides signal intensities(easy to identify patterns and trends)
  2. Adding annotation data in a single plot allows for a comprehensive view of the data.
  3. Provides a clear representation of gene locations.

Cons

  1. Not good choice to show signal intensity if the data contains sparse values.
  2. Gene annotation could overlap heatmap(Hard to distinguish individual annotations)

Version 3

Pros

  1. The line plot, plotted with all signals together mkae easy to compare all signals.
  2. Adding annotation data in a single plot provides good view of the data.
  3. Less subplots compare to Version 1(Make visualization less cluttered).

Cons

  1. Not ideal for visualizing dense signal data(as lines may overlap and obscure patterns)
  2. The annotations might become visually cluttered if there are too many genes or exons.

3. 2-mer counts in data

Task 3: 2-mer Occurrence Analysis in DNA Sequences

In this task, the file seq.txt was used, which contains DNA sequences with one sequence per line.

The goal was to analyze the positional distribution of 2-mers (subsequences of length 2) and visualize how frequently specific 2-mers occur at each position across all sequences.

For example, given the 2-mers "xx" and "yy" in the sequences:

TCTAAGGxxyyG

xxCGTGGyyCGT

TTTxxACCGyyG

AGCxxACAACyy

TAxxCAAyyAGT

The counts for each 2-mer by position would be:

  • "xx": [1 0 1 2 0 0 0 1 0 0 0 0]
  • "yy": [0 0 0 0 0 0 0 2 0 2 1 0]

Python code was provided to scan all sequences, count 2-mer occurrences at each position, and generate a figure illustrating these positional frequencies.

In[12]:
#defining function to count 2-mers
def count_kmers(sequences, kmers):
    kmer_counts = {kmer: [] for kmer in kmers}
    k = len(kmers[0])
    
    for i in range(len(sequences[0]) - k + 1):
        for kmer in kmers:
            count = 0
            for sequence in sequences:
                count += sequence[i:i+k] == kmer
            kmer_counts[kmer].append(count)
    
    return kmer_counts

#reading sequences from the text file
filename = "seq.txt"
with open(filename, 'r') as file:
    sequences = [line.strip() for line in file]


kmers = ["AA", "AC", "AG", "AT", "CA", "CC", "CG", "CT", "GA", "GC", "GG", "GT", "TA", "TC", "TG", "TT"] #define the k-mers


kmer_counts = count_kmers(sequences, kmers) #count occurrences of the k-mers at each position

#setting the Seaborn style
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
sns.set_palette("bright")
sns.set_palette("Spectral", len(kmers))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(19, 8)) #create line plots for each k-mer with broader figure size
for i, kmer in enumerate(kmers):
    counts = kmer_counts[kmer]
    non_zero_counts = [count if count >= 0 else None for count in counts]
    ax.plot(range(len(non_zero_counts)), non_zero_counts, label=kmer, linewidth=5.0)



#setting the axis labels and title
plt.xlabel('Position', fontsize=16)
plt.ylabel('k-mer count', fontsize=16)

#setting the size of the tick labels
ax.tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=14)
ax.tick_params(axis='y', labelsize=14)

ax.set_facecolor('white') #setting the background color to white

for spine in ax.spines.values():
    spine.set_color('black')

ax.legend(loc='upper left', framealpha=0.9, fontsize='large') #displaying the legend

plt.show()
